  {
    'body' => 'Hi.  Several messages (e.g., "Who cares?") have come through saying that 
the question of grids vs. coils is immaterial.  Of course this is true in 
a larger sense, but the question does have some relevance in terms of 
game play.  If ships do have a jump grid which lights up on exit/entrance 
to jump, several possibilities emerge:

1) You can detect ships much more easily as they jump in or out, and may 
be able to tell their size or other characteristics.
2) You may be able to tell where/how far they are jumping based on the 
pattern of grid activation.
3) A ship may be rendered incapable of jump or at least hampered even by 
minor damage (tears in the jump grid and the like).
4) Jump grids have implications for carrying strap-on cargo and modules.
5) etc.

As a GM, this can be important.  For instance, players ask "Can\'t we just
strap the ore to the outside of the ship?" and you say "No." and they ask
"Why not?"  You have to have some "canon" to fall back on.  Having
agreement on background details like this makes problem-solving by the
characters that much more interesting.  And the GM doesn\'t look like he\'s 
just arbitrarily handing down pronouncements.

Of course, as always, you can do whatever you want in your own universe.  
I think the debate here is simply to iron out what the canon from GDW is, 
how they\'ve changed it (if they\'ve changed it?), and what the relative 
merits/flaws of the old/new canon are.

There, my diplomatic deed for the day!  :)

Charles.

