    'topic' => 'The Joys of Anti-Grav',
    'body' => 'In TRAVELLER digest 521, stedee@auto-trol.com (Steve Deemer) inquired:

> Trying is visualize the Traveller future always seems (for me) to end up
> looking like today with spaceships. This shouldn\'t be the case, so I\'ve
> been wondering what the effect of having gravitic technology around for
> a few hundred years would have on peoples daily lives. We already got
> air/rafts and grav belts. Capitol is (was?) an entire complex suspended
> in mid-air. FGMPs have a gravitic recoil device. What else?

Well, for the most part, much Anti-grav technology is designed to lift
large payloads (or at least man sized payloads) but the use of smaller
technology for simpler low weight devices has a lot of potential.

One use was suggested by the movie Dune. (I don\'t recall reading about
it in the book, but I may be wrong)  There lights (presumably supported
by antigrav) would hover behind a person from a nice distance up, providing
soft spot light illumination wherever ehty went.  (Like some special
golf carts will do today.)  In the same book/movie, the Baron was 
extreemely overweight, in part because antigrav units kept the heart
from having to worry about all that fat.

Anti-grav seats, which don\'t actually keep you in the air but greatly
reduce the stress of going from a standing position to a seated one
on the legs, esp with the elderly, would be easy. Anti-grav eat in bed
tables can also be popular, and the weights here are also small.

On spaceships, low gravity areas might be interesting.  I recall an
interesting article with involved large scale space cities, where
the central area, contained a low gravity swimming pool.  (Hey
There, no splashing the water into the zero g area!)  But that was
based on a centripital gravity system which would graduate the
further down the radius you went, which is different from Anti-grav.

Star Trek, made popular the anti-grav-don\'t-get-a-hernia lifting
handles.  That is also a very important anti-grav development.

Ah well, just a few ideas from the top of my head.


 
