>in operation?

I believe Seeker are defunct since MT times but I might be wrong.

Steve Deemer (stedee@auto-trol.com) asked:

>Trying is visualize the Traveller future always seems (for me) to end up
>looking like today with spaceships. This shouldn\'t be the case, so I\'ve
>been wondering what the effect of having gravitic technology around for
>a few hundred years would have on peoples daily lives.

Yes, anti-grav or contra-grav makes a big difference. If I might draw an
analogy with AD&D, it\'s a bit like designing castles just like mediaeval
complexes and then remembering that in AD&D there are innumerable monsters
that can fly or burrow and magi who can teleport, create paths through 10\'
thick walls, etc...

i.e. yes, Traveller worlds which have heavy use of grav\' should be
appropriately different. Anywhere that criminals can have grav-belts, so
should the cops. Perhaps even window-cleaners for sky-scrapers!

However, there has to be a balance. I don\'t like too great a proliferation
of grav\' technology, partly because it is difficult to explain the
intricacies to the less technical players. Therefore I tend to limit grav\'
due to its cost. If you remember CT trav, the primary cost of an air/raft
(c. 500kCr?) was its grav gear; likewise a grav belt at 100kCr. Therefore I
averaged out grav tech as costing a minimum of about 50kCr for a base grav\'
module capable of supporting human weight. (I ought to compare this with the
lift ratings given in the CT Robots design book...) That would mean the
flower pot-suspension Steve mentioned in his post might cost several
thousand credits. Therefore it\'s the sort of posy thing that might be used
in yachts, fancy hotels, etc. but is never going to be seen in any
self-respecting spacers\' bar! Most of the time, the price difference between
grav\' and non-grav\' stuff will be such that normal citizens will go for
non-grav\'. It\'s handy but is it worth paying thousands of credits just to
save you carrying a box of tools?

However, I _do_ see big use in things like medecine where grav can help
disabled/injured people get around so much more easily.

Remember also that anti-grav\' takes power. And therefore requires batteries
as self-contained fusion plants, etc. do _not_ fit in anything smaller than
a backpack below TL14/15, in my campaign. (NB: Though the current research
into high voltage, \'high\' frequency power systems which are supposedly
releaseing \'Zero Point Energy\' and all this sort of thing might prove me
wrong sooner than some people expect - for the above, read "A bit like Cold
Fusion, but no one likes to talk about that at the moment").

