    'body' => 'Well, I watched the pilot, and I\'ve seen a few episodes since. As
others have noted, the plots vary all over the place. 

I disagree *violently* with those who think that the space scenes are
ok. As a series of stills, or even short clips, they are ok. But
anything more than that and we have some *real* problems.

Item:	on the Saratoga, the decks are *parallel* to the thrust axis. 

Even *with* articifial gravity, this is not a wise design decision, as
if the grav plates go out the corridors become *long* shafts. <Crunch>
(The sound of anyone in the corridors hitting the end when the engines
fire:-) 

Item:	These single seat fighters made it from Earth to Jupiter orbit
	in *one* hop in the pilot.

Ok, that makes them *better* than any ship in CT or MT or TNE. This is
hard to justify even with Isp 100k to 1M "fusion rockets".

It\'s also hard to justify having a *single* vehicle that can take off
from a runway, fly into orbit, and then go multiple AU. You could build
it, but in the atmosphere or low orbit, it\'d be carrying too much
wasted mass in the extra fuel and life support (and the way too
powerful engines). In deep space, the wings are wasted mass.

Any rational military would have *seperate* Aerospace fighters and deep
space fighters. Each optimized for their specialized job. And such
fighter would eat these things for lunch in their own operating environments.

Item:	In the pilot, they are waiting for a Chig attack force that is
	on its way to attack earth. They are *specifically* mentioned
	as hiding in the Trojan asteroids. They can see Jupiter and
	some of its moons.  They are also able to conduct a running
	battle with the Chigs as they pass through.

The Trojans are two groups of asteroids. They are in Jupiter\'s L4 and
L5 positions. That is, they are 60 degrees ahead and 60 degrees behind
it in the same orbit. That means that they are as far from Jupiter as
Jupiter is from the Sun! So much for seeing Jupiter.

Now, let\'s consider that battle. They are at rest with respect to the
asteroids. The Chigs are on a course that will get them to earth in a
time period suitable for a long range fighter (ie hours, not days!). 

Yet the relative velocities are shown as being nearly the same. We have
the the Marines and the Chigs *dogfighting*!! Heck, the relative
velocities shown can\'t be more than a few hundred km per hour!

And of course, we have the fighters making "Star Wars" type manuevers.
Banking on turns, and other things that work with aircraft but not
spacecraft. 

Oh yeah, they are close enough to *see* each other (actually, we
repeatedly see fighters pass within *meters* of each other!). 

Believable? Hell, no! *Star Trek* pays more attention to getting things
right than this series does.

