    'date' => 'Sun, 31 Dec 95 22:49:21 CST',
    'body' => '
>> Trying is visualize the Traveller future always seems (for me) to end up
>> looking like today with spaceships. This shouldn\'t be the case, so I\'ve
>> been wondering what the effect of having gravtic technology around for
>> a few hundred years would have on peoples daily lives. We already got
>> air/rafts and grav belts. Capitol is (was?) an entire complex suspended
>> in mid-air. FGMPs have a gravitic recoil device. What else?

I\'m taking it in an entirely different direction. <g> 

In my game universe gravity control comes at a *high* price!

Gravity control is accomplished with something I call an FGU
(Franklin Gravity Unit).  I make them small, cheap, low powered,
easy to build and available everywhere.  

There\'s just one little problem...they work by producing a field
that burns out microelectronic devices.  Everything electronic
has to be built with, at best, tube technology, and so is larger,
slower, more power hungry, etc.  Removing small powerful
computers changes the feel of the game a lot!  <g>

I had a exploration ship find a thriving civilization in one
scenerio that had advanced electronics, and (of course) hadn\'t
discovered the Franklin Effect.  Everywhere the players went they
blew all the circuits..made them most unpopular.

Eris Reddoch
ereddoch@amaranth.com


